import BlogHeader from "../../components/Header.astro";
import serverOverviewImg from "../../images/PZ_ARM_Overview.png";
import BlogLayout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import "../../styles/global.css";
---

<BlogHeader title="Setting Up Your Server" date="February 8, 2025" />
<script>
  import ClipboardJS from "clipboard";
  new ClipboardJS(".btn");
</script>

<BlogLayout
  title="Setting Up Your Server"
  description="A detailed guide on setting up your server from scratch."
>
  <div class="container max-w-7xl mx-auto bg-[#ffffff] p-10">
    <section class="max-w-none mx-auto mb-8">
      <h2>Introduction</h2>
      <p>
        Currently, Project Zomboid does not support ARM64 servers, making it
        difficult to set up a multiplayer server. We will use an emulator to
        bypass this restriction. This guide provides a step-by-step process for
        setting up a server using a working solution, suitable for beginners.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="max-w-none mx-auto my-8">
      <h2>Prerequisites</h2>
      <p>An Oracle Cloud VM instance with the following properties:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Ampere VM.Standard.A1.Flex OR VM.Standard.E2.1.Micro</li>
        <li>Canonical Ubuntu 22.04</li>
        <li>Open UDP ports 16261 & 16262 in Oracle firewall rules.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        If you're unfamiliar with setting up a VM instance using Oracle Cloud,
        check out this <a
          href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0kFjEUDJexI&list=WL&index=3&t=1215s"
          target="_blank"
        >
          video guide
        </a> (watch until 12:51 for the relevant parts).
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="max-w-none mx-auto my-8">
      <h2>Setting Up the Server</h2>
      <h3>1. Accessing the Terminal</h3>
      <p>
        Use your preferred method to access the terminal: [SSH / PuTTY (if you
        don't know how, watch the video)]
      </p>
      <h3>2. Root access</h3>
      Log in as root user if you don't want to continually add 'sudo' in front of
      every command.
      <pre><code>sudo su</code></pre>

      <h3>3. Update the System</h3>
      <p>Update and upgrade the package index:</p>
      <pre><code>sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get upgrade</code></pre>

      <h3>4. Set Up the Firewall</h3>
      <p>If not installed, install UFWaaaa:</p>

      <div class="relative flex bg-[#fef9f8] opacity-0.6">
        <pre><code id="code">sudo apt install ufw</code></pre>
        <button
          class="btn bg-[#e3f3f6] hover:bg-[#daf2f7] text-black rounded-md px-2 absolute right-0"
          data-clipboard-target="#code"
        >
          Copy
        </button>
      </div>
      <p>Enable UFW and allow the necessary ports:</p>
      <div class="relative flex bg-[#fef9f8] opacity-0.6">
        <pre><code id="code2">sudo ufw enable
sudo ufw allow 16261/udp
sudo ufw allow 16262/udp
sudo ufw reload</code></pre>
        <button
          class="btn bg-[#e3f3f6] hover:bg-[#daf2f7] text-black rounded-md px-2 absolute right-0 bottom-0"
          data-clipboard-target="#code2"
        >
          Copy
        </button>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="max-w-none mx-auto my-8">
      <h3>5. Install Docker</h3>
      <p>Run the following command to install Docker:</p>
      <div class="relative flex bg-[#fef9f8] opacity-0.6">
        <pre><code id="code3">curl -fsSL test.docker.com -o get-docker.sh && sh get-docker.sh</code></pre>
        <button
          class="btn bg-[#e3f3f6] hover:bg-[#daf2f7] text-black rounded-md px-2 absolute right-0 bottom-0"
          data-clipboard-target="#code3"
        >
          Copy
        </button>
      </div>
      <h3>6. Run the Docker Container</h3>
      <p>Pull the required Docker image and create a container:</p>
      <pre><code>docker pull teriyakigod/steamcmd:arm64</code></pre>
      <p>
        This container contains FEX-emulator which will allow us to run the PZ
        server.
      </p>

      <h3>7. Deploy and run the docker container</h3>
      <pre><code>run --entrypoint "/bin/sh" -p 16261:16261/udp -p 16262:16262/udp -it -u root teriyakigod/steamcmd:arm64</code></pre>
    </section>
    <section class="max-w-none mx-auto my-8">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">8. Install a Text Editor</h3>
      <p>
        Once inside the container as root, run the following command to install
        a text editor:
      </p>
      <pre><code>apt-get install nano</code></pre>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">9. Update the Package Index</h3>
      <p>Update the package index of the container with:</p>
      <pre><code>sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get upgrade</code></pre>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">10. Install Screen</h3>
      <p>
        To keep the server running even when the terminal is closed, install <code
          >screen</code
        >:
      </p>
      <pre><code>sudo apt install screen -y</code></pre>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">
        11. Define CPU Frequency for SteamCMD
      </h3>
      <p>
        Before running SteamCMD, define the CPU frequency. Open <code
          >steamcmd.sh</code
        > in a text editor and add this at the top or before <code
          >cd "$STEAMROOT"</code
        >:
      </p>
      <pre><code>export CPU_MHZ=2000</code></pre>
      <p>To exit and save, press <code>Ctrl + X</code>, then confirm.</p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">12. Launch the Zomboid Server</h3>
      <p>Login as the <code>steam</code> user and run SteamCMD:</p>
      <pre><code>sudo -u steam -i
cd Steam
FEXBash ./steamcmd.sh</code></pre>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">
        13. Install the Zomboid Server Files
      </h3>
      <p>
        In SteamCMD, log in as an anonymous user and install the Zomboid server
        files:
      </p>
      <pre><code>login anonymous
app_update 380870 validate</code></pre>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">14. Start the Zomboid Server</h3>
      <p>
        Navigate to the server files directory and use <code>FEXBash</code> and <code
          >screen</code
        > to run <code>start-server.sh</code>:
      </p>
      <pre><code>cd steamapps/common/Project\ Zomboid\ Dedicated\ Server/
FEXBash ./start-server.sh</code></pre>

      <p class="mt-4">
        Test if everything is working by connecting to the server using your
        public IPv4 address from the Oracle Cloud instance created at the start.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="max-w-none mx-auto my-8">
      <h2>Common Issues</h2>
      <p>
        If you encounter errors like <a
          href="https://theindiestone.com/forums/index.php?/topic/47417-dedicated-server-on-linux-vps-jre-crashes/"
          >this</a
        >, try the following:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Edit the <code>ProjectZomboid64.json</code> file.</li>
        <li>
          Change the <code>"UseZGC"</code> line to <code>"UseG1GC"</code>.
        </li>
        <li>Restart the server.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Keep the server running</h2>
      <p>
        Use <code>screen</code> to keep the server running in the background:
      </p>
      <pre><code>screen FEXBash ./start-server.sh</code></pre>
      <p>
        Detach from the session with <code>Ctrl + A</code>, then <code>D</code>.
      </p>
    </section>
